<TEXT>
a car carrying six people veered off a 
highway into a rainswollen creek saturday night and sank killing 
four young children officials and witnesses said 
witnesses said the station wagon ran into the north side of the 
pequea creek in this southeastern pennsylvania town and submerged 
about 40 feet out into the water at about 940 pm 
the driver donald duncan 27 of lancaster suffered critical 
injuries and a 13yearold girl heather cunrod who swam to shore 
as the car sank was in serious condition said officials at 
lancaster general hospital 
the children who died were identified as timothy cunrod 3 
jennifer cunrod 7 donald duncan 2 and jessica duncan 6 
assistant fire chief brian sullenberger said rescuers pulled the 
occupants out after winching the car to shore 
the car veered off a highway and crossed a parking lot before 
entering the creek near a railroad bridge witnesses said they 
didnt see brake lights before the car drove out into the water 
sullenberger said the driver apparently tried to kick out the 
windshield but failed a fire department vehicle arrived and pulled 
the car back to shore 
the creek a tributary of the susquehanna river was running 
high and the water was muddy because of recent rain 
kevin wimer manager of the pequea boat club said he watched as 
the car drove into the water 
it was like they never knew the creek was there wimer said 
