<TEXT>
twentythree gray whale carcasses have 
washed up on two remote islands south of kodiak and scientists 
planned a study to determine why the mammals died 
the concern is that we have a bunch of dead whales and we 
dont know the cause said steve zimmerman chief of the 
protected resources management division of the national marine 
fisheries service in juneau 
national marine fisheries service officials in a us coast 
guard helicopter flew to the beaches in the gulf of alaska on 
saturday and planned to examine the dead whales for two days 
they circled tugidak and sitkinak islands in the air to 
determine how many carcasses were there and spotted 14 whales on 
tugidak and nine on sitkinak 
the 23 are the largest number of dead grays ever discovered in 
the gulf said zimmerman whose agency is mandated by congress to 
protect the whales and monitor their population 
effects of last years exxon valdez oil spill in prince william 
sound were among possible reasons for the deaths but zimmerman 
said that was unlikely 
the gulf is on the migration path of the whales which travel 
from baja california to the bering sea every march 
the gray whale population is booming more than 20000 of the 
mammals were estimated to have migrated this year from their warm 
mexican lagoons to feeding grounds in icy alaska waters 
twentythree carcasses is a large number of dead whales 
certainly said don calkins a wildlife biologist with the alaska 
department of fish and game but the way the gray whale 
population is going it may not be that significant 
in fact the burgeoning population may play a part in the 
deaths authorities said 
it appears to be an indication of population stress said 
jim brooks a fisheries service deputy director in juneau 
brooks said the whales behavior lately has been odd for 
instance theyve been seen in places far off their migration path 
including in the waters near juneau hundreds of miles east 
if you get enough people or animals of any sorts youre going 
to get misfits brooks said 
the gray whales range from 36 to 50 feet long and are relatively 
thin when they arrive at alaska waters 
they are known to eat very little for the six months they remain 
at baja california the bering sea the vast body of water 
separating alaskas west coast from the soviet union provides the 
whales with an oceanbottom food supply of crustaceans 
authorities said carcasses found near kodiak may be the remains 
of weak animals unable to continue the journey north strong 
currents in the region could have washed the whales ashore 
scientist speculated 
</TEXT>
