<TEXT>
the 15 billion hubble space telescope is not a 
total loss despite the blurring of its giant eye by a misshapen 
mirror a scientist told a convention of astronomers on sunday 
eric chaisson an adjunct professor of physics at johns hopkins 
university said the troubled telescope still can provide 
scientists with information 
we can view bright objects with decent resolution but we 
wont be able to see the faintest objects in the universe 
chaisson said that frankly is what the hubble had made its 
name on that is compromised 
hubbles biggest mission was to peer into the universes distant 
corners 
the telescope launched april 25 has a focusing flaw that has 
sharply reduced its usefulness because of an error in the grinding 
and polishing of the hubbles main mirrors it cannot capture 
crisp clean pictures of distant stars 
an investigation into the problem is continuing the head of the 
nasa probe dr lew allen told congress last week that it may take 
more than six months to pinpoint the error in the telescope 
production 
chaisson is a senior scientist at the space telescope science 
institute in baltimore the group charged with overseeing hubbles 
scientific explorations 
when the convention of the astronomical society of the pacific 
was organized chaisson was slated to speak about hubbles early 
findings instead he found himself focusing on the hubbles woes 
in his presentation before several hundred astronomers 
youre going to have to stretch your imagination a little 
bit chaisson said there is a problem clearly we cant get 
around that but hubble is not broken there is still a lot of 
exciting science to come out of it 
chaisson showed a slide of the constellation orion taken by 
hubble that had slightly greater clarity than one taken from 
groudbased telescope 
hubble already shows starfields better than any groundbased 
telescope he said 
hubble had been expected to far surpass the capabilities of 
observatory telescopes which must peer up at the stars through 
earths atmosphere 
with its focusing problem hubble will be unable to pick out 
distant stars to determine the size of the universe chaisson said 
nor will it be able to search the heavens for objects invisible 
to groundbased telescopes like planets in other solar systems or 
extremely distant stellar objects he said 
chaisson held out hope that when replacement instruments are 
finally installed in 1993 hubble will be able to complete much of 
its mission over its planned 15year lifetime 
</TEXT>
