<TEXT>
for decades the sales tax in most states simply 
meant consumers had to pay a bit more money when they bought a car 
or a couch 
but the shift toward a servicebased economy has also brought 
changes in tax policy now when states are in a financial crunch 
they increasingly look to collect money each time a janitor mops a 
floor or even when an executive phones a lawyer for advice 
in massachusetts the state legislature recently passed a tax 
package that extends the sales tax to a broad range of services 
including accounting fees for businesses and athletic club 
memberships 
the move was a response to fiscal woes that over the last fiscal 
saw the state run up a deficit over 1 billion as its bond rating 
plummeted to the lowest ranking in the country 
while massachusetts is the latest state to consider taxing 
services some experts do not expect a rush to follow although a 
services tax may be tempting it also can be fraught with 
administrative headaches that means states probably will not take 
the step unless pushed by financial necessity 
talking about it is easier than implementing it said elaine 
leon director of taxpayer services for the department of revenue 
services in connecticut which last year widely expanded its 
services tax 
a handful of states tax some level of services but many others 
have attempted the move and failed 
florida enacted a wide range of service taxes in 1987 but 
repealed them before the end of the year observers however blame 
the repeal on a political firestorm that accompanied the tax 
package rather than administrative difficulties 
the sales tax generally dates to the great depression when many 
states looking for money applied a levy on the purchase of tangible 
property 
for most states the sales tax was set up at a time when the 
country was more of a manufacturingbased economy said stephen 
kidder the massachusetts commissioner of revenue thats what 
has shifted over time 
in fact some tax experts argue that many of the economic forces 
that prompted growth in the sales tax in the 1930s also exist in 
the 1990s making the taxation of services a stronger possibility 
nonetheless most states have been hesitant to move into the 
services tax reasons often cited include a fear that the tax will 
add costs to businesses which then will pass them along to 
consumers also critics say the tax can hurt competitiveness in 
individual states prompting some firms to locate elsewhere 
unlike cars or washing machines which are defined easily by 
their physical presence services have fuzzy boundaries and can be 
far less tangible 
for example connecticut taxes computer services a potentially 
broad sector and thus tried to tax hotel reservations since they 
rely on computers but the states supreme court decided last year 
that the tax should not apply because customers were paying for 
the reservations not the computer service leon said 
when asked how the state defines computer service leon said 
were still grasping with that 
also administering the tax becomes highly complex when levying 
transactions a multistate business has with another multistate 
firm 
roger feldman chairman of gaston amp snow a major boston law 
firm with offices around the country predicted massachusetts 
businesses would take their legal work outside the state to skirt 
the sales tax firms are likely to shift some of tasks to 
outofstate offices 
well try every legal means to avoid paying the tax feldman 
said 
tax experts say political inertia is a major factor working 
against service taxes 
for most politicians and taxpayers an old tax is a good 
tax said a report delivered last month to the federation of tax 
administrators a national group of state tax officials 
in substance this position argues that known evils are better 
than unknown evils the report said 
new mexico is one state without such worries its original sales 
tax from the depression included a tax on services said carolyn 
lindberg economic analyst with the new mexico taxation and revenue 
department 
as a result new mexico taxes most services excluding sales 
made by nonprofit institutions its accepted lindberg said 
though she added it comes as a shock to newcomers 
states that have tried more recently to adopt service taxes have 
used more of a laundry list approach identifying various services 
to be included but omitting others for example massachusetts 
plan exempts management consulting services even though accounting 
is included 
business and tax experts criticize this process saying it may 
meet political expediency but does not make economic sense 
everyone believes the future will have a different combination 
of taxes said james howell former chief economist at bank of 
boston but you cant draw it up in an arbitrary and pernicious 
way 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

