<TEXT>
an employee signs a waiver promising not 
to sue for age discrimination in return for a better severance 
package then turns around and sues anyway 
a sinking retailer tells a federal bankruptcy judge it needs to 
close a third of its stores and lay off 18000 employees to 
survive the judge rules that the retailer must negotiate with the 
workers on a severance package 
faced with increasingly complex labor laws and the need to trim 
work forces in a souring economy many companies are seeking legal 
advice on how to lay off workers lawyers say 
the advice is simple be careful said felix springer an 
attorney at day berry amp howard a hartford law firm that developed 
a seminar on how to lay off employees to satisfy a flood of 
corporate inquiries on the subject 
more than 120 corporate executives attended the seminar this 
spring in hartford and boston citing attorneyclient 
confidentiality the law firm wouldnt disclose the names of 
companies that sent representatives 
other law firms say they too are spending more time counseling 
corporate clients on steps they can take to reduce their work 
forces without opening themselves to wrongful termination or 
discrimination lawsuits 
its a big issue as the economy has turned sour its getting 
to be more and more of our practice said henry stewart a labor 
and employment lawyer at the boston firm palmer amp dodge 
new england is a focus of the trend because of its sagging 
economic fortunes and connecicut is a prime example its 
unemployment rate rose to 57 percent in april surpassing the 
national rate for the first time in 13 years 
nearly 30 percent of 480 companies that answered a recent survey 
by the connecticut business and industry association said they 
expect to reduce their work forces within the next three months 
springer said his firm advises managers to choose workers to be 
laid off based on objective criteria including job performance the 
value of their work to the company length of service and education 
level 
companies also are urged to offer employees assistance in 
finding new jobs as well as generous severance packages when 
possible he said 
workers who feel theyve been treated unfairly most commonly 
invoke two laws the federal age discrimination in employment act 
which covers those 40 and older and title 7 of the civil rights 
act of 1964 which prohibits employers from discriminating because 
of race religion sex or national origin 
but workers also are finding new and innovative ways to protect 
themselves 
more and more companies are asking employees to sign waivers 
promising not to sue for age discrimination in exchange for extra 
benefits usually an enhanced severance package 
that didnt stop two former employees from suing the cocacola 
bottling co of new york for age discrimination they claimed they 
were told they wouldnt receive an enhanced severance package after 
being let go unless they waived their right to sue under the age 
discrimination act 
the federal equal employment opportunity commission already 
concerned about such waivers joined the suit filed in us 
district court in bridgeport last year 
congress is considering legislation that would limit employers 
ability to offer extra benefits in exchange for an employee signing 
a waiver said paul brenner an eeoc attorney who specializes in 
age discrimination cases 
it has become a very serious problem that is that its 
cheaper to buy someone out with a waiver and then not have to worry 
about a lawsuit brenner said 
an estimated 18000 employees expected to lose their jobs when 
ames department stores inc closes 221 stores this summer recently 
won the right from a federal bankruptcy judge to negotiate with 
ames management on a severance package 
the move could have lasting impact analysts said bankruptcy 
proceedings could change dramatically if employees are made a party 
to such negotiations 
</TEXT>
