<TEXT>
the nations big three automakers open labor 
contract talks this week with the companies worried about 
declining profits and japanese competition and the union stressing 
job security 
the united auto workers union begins talks wednesday at general 
motors corp thursday at ford motor co and friday at chrysler 
corp the three national contracts covering more than 450000 auto 
workers expire at midnight sept 14 the first time in 11 years 
that all three expire at the same time 
each of the big three is cutting costs and its likely the 
union will be asked to pay a greater share of rising health and 
retirement benefits before benefits an average uaw assembler is 
paid nearly 15 an hour 
anthony st john chryslers chief negotiator has said that 
just maintaining the benefits in the current contract would boost 
chryslers labor costs 16 percent chrysler is in the worst 
financial shape of the big three 
the union will tell management that protecting existing jobs is 
its top priority health and safety on the job wages time off and 
pension improvements also are on the list 
the union has not had a strike since 1985 but the prospect this 
year has union members edgy families are paying off debts holding 
off on bigticket purchases and socking away whatever money they 
can 
i try to expect the worst and hope for the best said gary 
sorrell president of uaw local 977 at general motors corps 
marion ind metal fabricating plant he said he and his wife 
joyce canceled this years vacation 
the uaw left the signing ceremonies of the last contracts 
bragging it had won job security because the companies were allowed 
to close plants only when sales of the product made there fell 
since 1988 however gm and chrysler have used that clause to 
close six assembly plants putting 17000 workers on the street 
the japanese in the same period have opened three us assembly 
plants and announced plans for expansion of another 
in june 1988 the big threes combined share of the nations car 
and truck market was 744 percent the japanese companies held 192 
percent during the next two years the big three lost nearly 3 
percentage points the japanese gained almost 5 points 
you have to treat plant closings as you do a national 
disaster said franklin sherman of uaw local 1005 in parma ohio 
youre talking about 3000 or 4000 people losing their jobs 
the uaw set its bargaining agenda at a convention in may 
president owen bieber pleaded with delegates to give bargaining 
committees broad flexibility 
yet there was militant talk at the convention its widely 
believed gm will be targeted for a strike this year 
auto analyst ron glantz of dean witter reynolds inc in san 
francisco calls a strike against gm likely john kirnan an analyst 
with kidder peabody amp co of new york said chances for a 
widespread strike are better this year than in the past 20 years 
the last nationwide strike by the uaw against an automaker was 
in 1985 when about 70000 chrysler workers walked out for 12 days 
negotiations usually start slowly bargainers meet through july 
and august in subcommittees focusing on contract clauses dealing 
with specific issues 
sometime around labor day the uaw chooses one of the companies 
as a target talks at the other two companies are suspended until 
settlement with the target is reached that contract then is taken 
to the others modified slightly and brought to the rankandfile 
for a vote 
but socalled pattern bargaining may disappear this year 
chrysler which reported an 80 percent decline in firstquarter 
earnings is seen as most likely to break the pattern during its 
financial crisis in the early 1980s chrysler extracted concession 
contracts from the uaw 
finances are better at gm and ford but gms firstquarter 
profits this year were 54 percent below last year fords were down 
69 percent 
another factor in this years talks is the aging work force and 
the increasing number of retirees the average age of the big three 
auto workers is 42 compared with under 30 in the japanese plants 
demands for retiree costofliving protection has led to 
numerous protests by older union members another such 
demonstration is planned for wednesday morning outside gm 
headquarters 
wally kijek a member of local 1005 in parma said that cost of 
living adjustments or colas for retirees could be the ultimate 
end to that job security issue the guy who is growing into 
retirement right now can rest assured that he will have an 
equitable wage when he gets out there 
