<TEXT>
allegheny international inc has taken a major 
step toward emerging from chapter 11 bankruptcy protection as a 
judge approved a 50 million settlement of a creditor lawsuit 
the 13 billion suit was filed against allegheny 
internationals bank lenders by the companys unsecured creditors 
us bankruptcy judge joseph l cosetti late last week called 
the proposed settlement fair reasonable and essential to the 
smallappliance manufacturers chances of emerging from bankruptcy 
the banks will make no cash payments but they agreed to give up 
their right to receive 39 million of the 57 million in interest 
their loans to allegheny international accrued from the companys 
feb 20 1988 bankruptcy filing through feb 29 of this year plus 
all interest accrued after that date 
interest has accrued at the rate of about 2 million a month 
allegheny international which makes sunbeam and oster 
appliances has paid no interest because such payments are not 
permitted while under bankruptcy protection it is to make the 
payments once it emerges from bankruptcy 
the interest being forfeited by the banks will be given to 
unsecured creditors and shareholders in the forms of stock and 
warrants the banks also agreed to absorb their legal fees for 
which they usually could receive reimbursement from allegheny 
international 
allegheny international meanwhile agreed to provide legal 
indemnity of up to 3 million to the banks arising out of other 
claims that could arise from deals that prompted the suit 
the creditors who later were joined by shareholders claimed in 
their may 1988 complaint that institutions led by mellon bank 
doomed the company to bankruptcy at the expense of other 
creditors when they forced the company in 1986 to accept a harsh 
new loan agreement 
